node.text: Introducing Sipping With, a new series hosted by Contributing Editor Sean Flynn (@travelingnewyorker), who’s taking us behind the bar at world-renowned restaurants, hotels, and resorts to see how the best in the business craft specialty cocktails. On this episode, Sean visits @themarkhotelny, where Bartender Ken Ziegler shows us how to make a ginger margarita — a fresh take on the classic. We hope you’ll follow along and sip with us at home. Cheers!

node.title: Learn How One of the Best Hotels in NYC Makes Its Signature Margarita

node.text: In the latest installment of our Walk With T+L series, you can tour Disney World's Magic Kingdom with an Imagineer and uncover the design secrets you might have missed during your last visit. We’ll visit the exclusive Cinderella Castle Suite, the Beauty and the Beast-themed Be Our Guest Restaurant, and so much more. Come along as we get an inside look at how Disney “makes magic real” — the theme of the Magic Kingdom.

node.title: Uncover the Magic Kingdom's Design Secrets With a Disney Imagineer

node.text: In this new video series, Walk With T+L, we'll be taking you on some of the best walking tours across the globe. On this episode: the island of Amorgos, Greece. The Greek Islands are on just about everyone's bucket list. But like many of the world’s most photogenic destinations, over-tourism has become a real issue. Luckily, there are more than 200 inhabited islands in Greece, meaning you can get all of the beauty and none the crowds on some of the lesser-known islands, like Amorgos. Come along! Tour by @_thebluewalk

node.title: This Greek Island Has All of the Beauty and None of the Crowds

node.text: In this new video series, Walk With T+L, we'll be taking you on some of the best walking tours across the globe. On this episode: Paris, France. A city that needs no introduction, Paris may as well be synonymous with food, culture, fashion, and architecture. Despite being a bucket-list destination for millions of people, the French capital still holds plenty of hidden secrets beyond the Eiffel Tower and world-class museums. Join us on this walking tour to see for yourself. Tour by @walkstours

node.title: Jet Off to Paris From the Comfort of Your Home on This Virtual Walking Tour

These stories will give insight into the historic work of the Underground Railroad and the experiences of the individuals who traveled it in hopes of escaping slavery. Come along. Tour by @manumissiontour

node.text:
1990s: "I grew up in the 90s — Nirvana, flannel shirts, my first Hotmail account. It was also a time of great change. Some our covers during this period feel more like documentation of history — the October 1990 'Moscow Now' moment, with young Soviet fashion students in Red Square, shot by Bob Adelman, gets me every time.
. 
Then there’s an image of a bodybuilder on Ipanema Beach in Rio from November 1993 that feels utterly transportive. Still. And seeing fashion designer Issac Mizrahi (@imisaacmizrahi) posing on the streets of London in October 1997 is pure fun. The cover under editor Nancy Novogrod signals a shift towards globalization, star designers, and yes, influencers. Isaac is an OG." -T+L Editor in Chief @jacquigiff
.
Throughout this week, we've been looking back on the past five decades of T+L covers and exploring what they can teach us about how travel has evolved. Check our feed every day for a new post, and join us in celebrating 50 years of T+L!

node.text:
This week on Behind the Views: Ines Fiorini (@pinkines). Ines first developed an interest in iPhone photography when Instagram was just an emerging platform. But, while studying in Paris to get her PhD, she fell in love with capturing beautiful places along her travels. “I had the opportunity to explore one of the world’s most beautiful cities everyday. I took pictures of everything I saw and learned how to be more confident behind the camera,” she says. 
.
Ines’s approach to travel photography: “I’m curious about everything. This is the best way to find new things and special angles even in places you've already seen,” she says. “When I shoot, I wait for that feeling that makes you think to yourself, ‘Yes! That’s exactly what I wanted’.”
.
When asked about her advice for aspiring photographers, she says, “Be curious and always stay true to yourself. Taking pictures — a lot of pictures — is the best way to improve and evolve your personal style. Inspiration is everywhere around us, and social media is a great source too.”
.
In Ines’s go-to camera bag you’ll find: a Sony Alpha 7r III camera, Sony Zeiss 12-24 mm, Sony Zeiss 24-70 mm, and Sony Zeiss 70-200 mm lenses, a GoPro Max, a DJI Mavic Pro drone, and a lightweight tripod.
.
All photos by @pinkines.

2000s: "A momentous decade, very much defined by one event: 9/11. There was a downturn in travel, and then a major boom in travel. New airlines launched. People were on the move, especially in the United States (see our June 2002 gem).
. 
Celebrities started to be on the cover of every magazine — including T+L. I love the energy of our Salma Hayek (@salmahayek) cover story shot in the Bahamas, in November 2004.
. 
Striking entryways were also very much a thing, the precursor to every arched doorway you’ve ever spotted on someone’s Instagram grid. See our June 2000 Hotels Issue cover, celebrating the debut of Amanjena, in Morocco." -T+L Editor in Chief @jacquigiff
.
Throughout this week, we're looking back on the past five decades of T+L covers and exploring what they can teach us about how travel has evolved. Check our feed every day this week for a new post, and join us in celebrating 50 years of T+L!

2010s: "People! Places! Things! With the rise of social media platforms like Instagram, Facebook, Pinterest, and Twitter, T+L covers had to change to keep up with the over-saturation of travel photography.
. 
You can see a shift over the years: less copy, more emphasis on the photo to tell the story. The first cover, shot by David Cicconi (@davidcicconistudio) from July 2010, showcases food, in such an unexpected way, by bringing the bakers from Amedeo Giusti in Lucca into the street. You just want to rip off a hunk of that focaccia and start eating! 
.
The rooftops of Florence — and that magical, romantic light — shot by Annie Schlechter (@annieschlechter) pair perfectly with the idea of a dream trip. 
.
For our July 2018 Adventure Issue, the Ingalls (@ingallsphoto) captured this vivid under-the-water-snorkel scene in Hawaii; you could be right there with the swimmer, reaching out to touch the turtles.
.
And a personal favorite of mine is this kangaroo, shot by Sean Fennessy (@seanfennessy) for our December 2019 Destination of the Year cover. It’s a moment in time, a moment in nature, a reminder of the power of travel." -T+L Editor in Chief @jacquigiff
